sentence:
President Donald Trump once said trade wars are “good, and easy to win.” But the stock market and many fund/retirement portfolios are becoming casualties of a war, which investors are asking, “what is it good for?” Corporate CEOs are responding, “absolutely nothing.”

Investors were caught off guard Thursday evening after President Trump, seeking to stem the flow of migrants across the U.S. border, announced plans to impose tariffs on imports from Mexico.
The President says Mexico could face a 5% tariff on all goods coming into the country, unless Mexico “STOP” the flow of illegal migrants into the U.S.
He said the tariffs will increase to 10% on July 1 if there’s no improvement, and will rise by another 5% every month, up to 25% by Oct. 1 if the crisis persists.
“Tariffs will permanently remain at the 25% level unless and until Mexico substantially stops the illegal inflow of aliens coming through its territory,” Trump said.
The threat to Mexico, one of America's largest and most important trading partners, sparked another wave of selling on Wall Street Friday, with the market logging its worst May since 2010.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average declined 354.84 points Friday, or 1.4%, to close 24,815.04.
Aside from falling to a four-month lows, the Dow also lost a psychological benchmark by closing below 25,000.
The S&P 500 index fell 36.80 points, or 1.3%, to close at 2,752.06, while the tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite dropped 114.57 points, or 1.5%, to close at 7,453.15.
On a weekly basis, the picture was more worrisome.
The Dow lost 3%, marking its sixth straight weekly decline and its longest weekly losing streak since June 2011.
For the week, the S&P 500 was off by 2.6%, while the Nasdaq shed 2.4%.
Slowing economic growth and potential business disruption is at the forefront when assessing investor’s risk appetite.
When including everything from auto parts and avocados to beer and televisions, some $346 billion of goods were imported from Mexico into the United States last year.
This puts many U.S. corporations such as General Motors (GM) and Ford (F), which on Friday lost 4% and 2%, respectively, at the mercy of the tariffs.
Meanwhile denim maker Levi Strauss (LEVI), which has exposure to both Mexico and China, saw its stock plunge 7%.
An estimated 20% of its jeans and apparel sold the United States are made in Mexico and China.

While recent economic data (U.S. unemployment, wage growth and inflation) remain broadly positive about the the direction of the economy, growth and profit expectations will have to be reset until there’s a resolution with trade.
During the month of May, both the Dow and S&P 500 suffered nearly 7% declines, while the Nasdaq tumbled 8% — its worst May since 2010.
Are these buying opportunities?
It’s tough to say.
The biggest question investors must now reconcile is can the United States successfully win two trade wars at the same time?
In other words, though I believe equities will be fine in the long run (12 to 18 months), investors should tread lightly.
Here are this week’s stocks to keep an eye on.
Wall Street expects Coupa to lose 4 cents per share on revenue of $73.85 million.
This compares to the year-ago quarter when it lost 1 cent per share on revenue of $56.35 million.
What to watch: Shares of Coupa, which are up 104% year to date, have stemmed the tide amid the recent selloff in tech and, in particular, software stocks.

The provider of a cloud-based corporate spend management software makes money by analyzing large quantities of corporate transactional expense data, looking for spending patterns and areas of inefficiency.
The Coupa platform provides customers with actionable insights that can lead to improved inventory management, smarter purchasing decisions, while lowering expenditures.
This business spend management industry has a total addressable market valued at $37 billion.
And the Coupa's strong revenue growth (up 39% in F2019 and 40% in F2018) suggests it is causing some disruption.
Wall Street expects Salesforce to earn 61 cents per share on revenue of $3.68 billion.
This compares to the year-ago quarter when earnings came to 52 cents per share on revenue of $3.01 billion.
What to watch: Software stocks have been punished during the recent selloff.
And Salesforce, despite its success, hasn’t escaped the wrath.
Shares of the cloud computing giant have fallen more than 8% over the past thirty days.
Investors who have waited for a better entry point can do well here, given the company’s projected earnings growth rate of 27.5% annually over the next five years.
Salesforce’s customer relationship management services are a must-have for many companies looking to add capabilities such as sales, marketing, e-commerce and analytics.
As such, Salesforce’s guidance and its billings forecast will be closely-watched on Tuesday to assess the direction of the stock.
Wall Street expects Stitch Fix to lose 3 cents per share on revenue of $395.06 million.
This compares to the year-ago quarter when earnings came to 2 cents per share on revenue of $295.91 million.

What to watch: Stitch Fix shares, which have been under pressure from competitive threats like Amazon (AMZN), have rebounded impressively, rising more than 35% year to date, besting the 9% rise in the S&P 500 index.
The subscription fashion retailer has been rewarded for a strong Q2 during which it beat EPS estimates by 7 cents, while revenue surged 25%, topping forecast by more than $5 million.

To keep the stock in its upward trajectory, on Wednesday Stitch Fix CEO Katrina Lake, who has done a masterful job growing the company’s active clients base, must convince a skeptical analyst community that the company can be profitable.
Wall Street will also listen closely to how Stitch Fix plans to disrupt the traditional apparel industry as we know it.

Beyond Meat (BYND) - Reports after the close, Thursday, Jun 6

Wall Street expects Beyond Meat to lose 15 cents per share on revenue of $38.93 million.
This will be the company’s first earnings report as a public issue.
What to watch: Calling Beyond Meat’s IPO a success would be a an under-statement.
Thanks to surging consumer demand owing to tailwinds from its well-differentiated product offering, BYND stock price has skyrocketed from a $25 IPO pricing to over $100 in less than a month.

And despite concerns about valuation and the company’s ability to grow in a market where larger players like Tyson Foods (TSN) and Hormel Foods (HRL) exist, Beyond has tons of support from the market.

For the stock price to continue to rise, however, on Thursday the company must affirm the belief that it can successfully disrupt the traditional meat marketplace and outline its path towards profitability.
Wall Street expects DocuSign to earn 5 cents per share on revenue of $208.15 million.
This compares to the year-ago quarter when earnings were 1 cent per share on revenue of $155.81 million.
What to watch: Investors who missed the buying opportunity when I last spoke about this company must now buying it at a more expensive price.
After a 33% plunge at the end of November, the stock is now up 40% so far in 2019.
And given the company’s projected growth rate, there is no sign of slowing down DocuSign, which provides individuals and businesses the ability to digitize an agreement process.
One of the most successful IPOs of the 2018, DocuSign on Thursday must continue to show not only a re-acceleration of revenue but also outline its path towards profitability.
Wall Street expects Zoom to break earn 1 cent per share on revenue of $111.73 million.
This will be the company’s first earnings report as a public issue.

What to watch: One of the most successful tech IPOs in recent memory, Zoom aims to disrupt the video conferencing market, which, is riddled with technical issues despite a decade-long attempts by larger players to simplify the experience.
Some 90% of all virtual meetings within corporations still utilize only audio as business opt to avoid the hassle often associated with integrating video.
Zoom’s video-first platform, which is based on the cloud, is disruptive in its ease of use.
Combined with its higher-quality video offering and its 24/7/365 customer support, the company has attracted a loyal customer base.
On Thursday Wall Street will want to see how this loyalty translates to making money.
